st, Sussex, England":"Penhurst, Sussex, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1325–1370":"1325–1370","1325–Female":"1325–Afdød","1355–1389":"1355–1389","1300–1345":"1300–1345","1300–Female":"1300–Afdød","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1389":"1389","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1345":"omkring 1345","1370":"1370","1328":"1328","Sussex, England. United Kingdom":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Lewes, Sussex, England":"Lewes, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Penhurst, Sussex, England":"Penhurst, Sussex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1325–1370":"1325–1370","1325–Female":"1325–Overleden","1355–1389":"1355–1389","1300–1345":"1300–1345","1300–Female":"1300–Overleden","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1389":"1389","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1345":"circa 1345","1370":"1370","1328":"1328","Sussex, England. United Kingdom":"Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Lewes, Sussex, England":"Lewes, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Penhurst, Sussex, England":"Penhurst, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1325–1370":"1325–1370","1325–Female":"1325–Deceased","1355–1389":"1355–1389","1300–1345":"1300–1345","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1389":"1389","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1345":"about 1345","1370":"1370","1328":"1328","Sussex, England. United Kingdom":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Lewes, Sussex, England":"Lewes, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Penhurst, Sussex, England":"Penhurst, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sidney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Durham):","habitational name from Sidney Farm in Alfold (Surrey), from Old English <i>sīd</i> ‘large, spacious, long’ (dative <i>sīdan</i>) + <i>ēg</i> ‘island’.","possibly also a habitational name from any of the places called Saint-Denis in Normandy, named from the dedication of their churches to Saint Dionysius (see   Dennis  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Dennis","meanings":["English: from the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Denis(e)</i>, <i>Dinis(e)</i>, vernacular forms of Latin <i>Dionysius</i>, Greek <i>Dionysios</i> ‘(follower) of <i>Dionysos</i>’, an eastern god introduced to the classical pantheon at a relatively late date and bearing a name of probably Semitic origin. The name was borne by various early Christian saints, including Saint Denis, the martyred 3rd-century bishop of Paris who became the patron saint of France. From the 12th century onward, the popularity of the name in England (and of its cognates, mainly   Denis  , in the continental Europe) seems to have been largely due to French influence. The feminine form <i>Dionysia</i> (in vernacular English likewise <i>Den(n)is</i>) is also found, and some examples of the surname may originate from it.","English: from Middle English <i>deneis</i>, a variant of <i>danais</i> ‘Danish’, with the vowel influenced by Middle English <i>denshe</i> (Old English <i>denisc</i>). Compare   Dence  .","Irish (mainly Dublin and Cork): of the same origin as 1 and 2 above, sometimes an alternative form to   Donohue   but more often to   McDonough  , since the personal name <i>Donnchadh</i> was Anglicized as <i>Donough</i> or <i>Denis</i>."]},{"name":"Sydney","meanings":["English and Scottish (Midlothian): variant of   Sidney  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William Sidney was born in 1325, in Lewes, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Sidney II, was 25 and his mother, Helen Batisford, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Johanna Brokhull. He died in 1370, in Surrey, England, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1325–1370":"1325–1370","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1355–1389":"1355–1389","1300–1345":"1300–1345","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1389":"1389","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1345":"umbes 1345","1370":"1370","1328":"1328","Sussex, England. United Kingdom":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Lewes, Sussex, England":"Lewes, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Penhurst, Sussex, England":"Penhurst, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1325–1370":"1325–1370","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","1355–1389":"1355–1389","1300–1345":"1300–1345","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1389":"1389","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1453":"1453",